post_text: On Tuesdays, FLSD provides weekly meals for Finneytown families. This week, we served 185 families, 498 children, times 10 meals for a total of 4,980 meals. We continue to thank you LaSoupe and O Pie O for the weekly donations of meals for our families! If you are in a position to help O Pie O continue to provide healthy meals for students, please visit their Facebook page or website for ways to assist! Thank you to Milford Food Service and all the volunteers every week and everyone who helps makes this happen weekly!

post_text: Finneytown Families: We understand many of you are out of power right now in addition to staying at home. While all of this presents many challenges, just know, we'll get through this together! We are thinking about you and hope everyone is safe from the storms and damage last night. Please continue to stay safe and home. With many power lines down and roads blocked by trees, please keep your distance and stay at home where you are safe. If anyone has been affected by the storm damage, please reach out to district administration if we might help. We hope to see you all soon!

post_text: Outstanding! Our staff is truly making this experience one filled with humor and care! Huge applause to all our staff just doing what it takes!

Jennifer Prengaman Ortiz‎Finneytown Elementary PTA
March 31 at 12:07 PM ·

Our district is awesome. Just picked up food, and not only did seeing some staff make me smile, but it was super efficient, very successfully social distancing, and there were TWO t-rexes there! Parents, it may actually be worth taking your kids for the ride to pick up food. 😀. #flsdBetterTogether
(Picture description: person in a t-rex dinosaur costume standing outside the school, framed by the window of my car because I took the picture from my seat while stopped)

post_text:
Good evening Finneytown Families,

Don't forget that meal pick up is TODAY from 11 am to 1 pm at Brent Elementary. You must have your children with you to pick up food. Each child will receive breakfast and lunch for 5 days. You will stay in your car and volunteers will bring the food to you.

After this message, another message will come that is for our Nepali families. Feel free to hang up or delete as you most likely will not understand it. We just want to be sure all of our families get the information.

The next food pick up after tomorrow will be next Tuesday, March 31st at the Secondary Campus. It will still be a drive up where you stay in your car but you won't have to have the children with you.

Enjoy the rest of Spring Break. Remote Learning begins again on Monday!

post_text: How about one of our famous grads? Thanks for the shout-out Joe Rebman!
shared_text:
HARPCOLUMN.COM
Harp Column Podcast Episode 58 - Harp Column

Joe Rebman
December 17, 2019 at 11:49 AM ·

I'm so excited to share my third(!!!!) entry with Harp Column, this time in the form of a podcast with Kristina Finch! In the episode we discuss my teaching at Cincinnati's School for Creative and Performing Arts, Northern Kentucky University, and the adventure to create and premiere my concerto "Hyperion" at the Mostly Modern Festival with Robert Paterson!

Also shout out to Finneytown Local School District! Their name didn't make it into the podcast, but I do talk about how they are the reason I started composing! Yay public school!

post_text:
Attention BRENT Parents: The power just went out at Brent. A transformer went out in the neighborhood. Power won't be restored until this afternoon. Students need to leave because school will be closed today.

Students who take the bus will be sent home on the bus starting at 9 am. Someone must be home to meet the child.

If your child does not ride a bus, please make arrangements to pick him/her up NOW!

If YOUR CHILD GOES TO DAYCARE FROM A BUS, PLEASE CONTACT DAYCARE TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS. WE CAN DROP OFF BUT THEY NEED TO BE PREPARED TO HAVE THEM THERE.

No power means no heat so we must clear everyone out of the building now before it gets too cold.

If you have questions, please call 513-728-3700,

Thank you,

Terri Noe
Superintendent
